Background:¶

Based on my research of the problem overall I came across several abstracts that other people have completed who came across several different conclusions and regression models to solve this problem. One even posted their finding with a linear regression model that was 51% accurate.

  • To be able to predict the success of any given movie based on the traits related to the given example as it compares to the IMDB database.
  • The data I'd use as a data analyst would include and reference the following items: budget, previous lead actor success, budget specific for marketing as well as if it was a sequel,prequel or orginal concept.
  • Duration,facebook popularity of director as well as the top 3 actors in the film and finally the number faces in the poster.

Business intelligence¶

In [23]:
sns.lmplot(x='duration',y='imdb_score',hue='content_R',data=nw2)
Out[23]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0xe04c940>

Orange being R rated Blue being not an R rated movie.

So in comparision of score to duration we can see that an R rated movie does much better than a non-R rated movie if its duration is less than 150 minutes tho overall R rated movies did much better overall compared to non-R.

In [24]:
sns.lmplot(x='duration',y='imdb_score',hue='content_G',data=nw2)
sns.lmplot(x='duration',y='imdb_score',hue='content_NC-17',data=nw2)
sns.lmplot(x='duration',y='imdb_score',hue='content_PG',data=nw2)
sns.lmplot(x='duration',y='imdb_score',hue='content_PG-13',data=nw2)
Out[24]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0xfb621d0>

Here we can see the difference on well a specific content type of movie did based on its duration to the Imdb score. Where G movies did much better than non-G movieswhen there duration went under roughly 90 minutes. PG movies had an almost exact correlation between their imdb score and duration where the longer the movie the generally better they did. While NC-17 movies were the only to have an inverse correlation from duration to score where the top NC-17 movies had less than 50minutes on average.

Here we can see the previously related variables correlated with eachother with relative content rating.

Where if the movie has a R rating it has a massively increased chance to gain a high imdb score over G,PG and NC-17 while pg-13 generally has inverse relationship with its Imdb score.

As well as the more people who voted and reviewed greatly increased how well the movie did,meaning the higher popularity generally means better review on imdb.

Yet surprisingly there is little to no correlation between gross or profit compared to the imdb score. Here most people would assume the more money you have to spend the better it'll do.

Storytelling¶

To start we have to make a few hypothesis and assumptions about the data we are dealing with. The first thing I did was skim through and look for any data that I felt would be impactful as it compares to both what what they consider succesful (the imdb score) and what I'd consider success for a movie(the profit).

After contemplating this I went and began cleaning of this data set to narrow it down from roughly 5K to 3756 completed filled rows. From here I began simplifying and prepping the content rating what i believed may be a big impact on the score. I converted all old ratings to current ratings then converted the 5 ratings (G, PG, PG-13, R and NC-17) into dummy variables to check their correlation to both profit and IMDB score.

Then I began my analysis on each content_rating and how it compares to each other content_rating as it is on imdb_score by duration. where we see that shorter R movies do significantly better than non-R. This is then interesting when we see each rating as it compares to other ratings. The only rating to stick out the most is the NC-17 movies where its duration is inverselty related to its imdb score. meaning extremely short NC-17 movies have an extremely high chance of doing well as it compares to an imdbscore.

StoryTelling pt.2¶

Several of ours models once made for the proper variables came out at average or above average on all results coming out to about a 50% success rate on 4 options so thats not awful. Variables I deemed relevant/correlation showed was the most relevant were the following: Duration Gross number voted users number user for reviews budget movie facebook likes profit and the various content ratings (G,PG,PG-13,R[all others were consolidated into these])

Through several versions of testing and long waiting periods I always able to test up to currently 10,000 random forest regressions. The results from this were very appealing we ended with an average success rate of 77% which seemed amazing compared to other results. Further testing in more extreme numbers will ensue. However when we break it down the regression model had a 100% accuracy when figuring out which movies were considered to be bad, these movies had an IMDB of 2 or less. The second highest accuracy being figuring out what is considered an excellent movie, movies with an IMDB of 8 or more. Sadly, our worst success was in both ok and good movies, the largest range categories.

Beyond here I began doing increasingly higher interpretation to determine wheather more estimators would ever actually continue to increase the statistical correctness of the random forest regression model. See the following for 50K estimators and no actual increase in overall accuracy.

#find optimal K (elbow method)
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist 

K = range(1, 10) 

meandistortions = []

for k in K: 
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1) 
    kmeans.fit(nwML_norm) 
    meandistortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(nwML_norm, kmeans.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / nwML_norm.shape[0]) 

plt.plot(K, meandistortions, 'bx-') 
plt.xlabel('k') 
plt.ylabel('Average distortion') 
plt.title('Selecting k with the Elbow Method')
